text.tspan: - folded twice to make a triangle
- webbing folded in two to attach D-ring
- make one for each shoulder strap

tspan.tspan: Posterior panel
- cut PALS webbing to the same lenght as the witdth of the
posterior panel
- the PALS webbing ends are sewin into the seam of the
posterior and intermediate panel
- compression strap bluckle receptacels can also be sew into
the ends of the PALS webbing instead of using dedicated webbing
loops for the buckles.
- velco loop patch considered mandatory because they are fun

text.tspan: - sew the posterior panel to the posterior edge of this panel
- sew the posterior edge of the main zipper to the anterior edge of this panel

tspan.tspan: Intermediate panel anterior section
- Sew the anterior edge of the main zipper to the posterior edge of
this panel
- Sew the storm flap to the posterior edge of this panel
- Sew the anterior panel to the anterior edge of this panel
- to get the PALS webbing lined up with the PALS webbing on the
posterior panel it is best to mark where they should be by pinning
this panel to the posterior panel and using that as a guide (assuming
you've already completed the posterior panel, or at least marked the
location of the PALS webbing on it)

text.tspan: fold 1 cm and stich for a finished edge
Interior hydration pocket for the anterior panel
- on the interior face of the anterior panel
- add a few cm width to the pocket to give space
for the hudration bladder. if the anterior exterior panel
if the same width as the hydration pocket panel, the pack
will buldge out against the wearers back

tspan.tspan: Bottom Panel
- This panel is drawn much too tall here.
- Trim it to the appropriate size by comparing it to the width of the finished intermediate
panel.
- The bottom panel lateral edge should be the same length as the medial edge on the
intermediate panel
- Sew the posterior edge to the posterior panel inferior egde
- Sew the anterior edge to the anterior panel inferior edge
- Sew the lateral edges to the the medial edges of the intermediate panel. NOTE: the edges are
not designed to meet up, the intermediate panel is intentionally too long. The bottom panel
simply covers the medial edges of the intermediate panel, and closes the gap between the theo
medial edges.
Storm Flap
- This piece pill cover the main sipper on the pack to protect it from
wear as well as preven rainwater entering the pack through the zipper
- fold lengthwise at the middle.
- Sew a seam along the fold to make a sharper, more clean looking fold
- This flap ends up being relatively large. It could be smaller.
Fold the last 1 inch of the
compression straps back on itself,
and secure the fold with a bartack.
This will prevent the webbing from
exiting the buckle by mistake

text.tspan: Interior zipper pockets for the posterior panel
- Sew onto the interior face of the posterior panel

tspan.tspan: This edge is sewn into the seam
between the anterior panel and
the intermediate panel
This drawing is originally a SVG (scalable vector graphics) file. I've not called out
deminsions, since everything is drawn to-scale. Both a SVG and PDF version can be opened
with a vector drawing program such as Inkscape to see the dimensions of any part. A scale
bar is provided at the top just in case.
Seam allowances are either 1 cm or 1.5 cm, and are indicated by a darker color.
Anterior panel
- the webbing for the shoulder strap superior connection
point can be sewn either on the exterior on interior face
of the panel. It is simpler to sew them to the exterior
face, as it can be done before the final assembly of the
pack. Else the webbing must only be bartacked in the seam
allowance, and finalised after final assembly.
